Within the Lamiaceae, the Mints (
 Mentha) are of economical relevance, and have a long history of human use as aromatic and medical compounds. This genus comprises around 30 species of aromatic perennial herbs, distributed mostly in temperate and sub-temperate regions of Eurasia, Australia, Africa, and North America (
 Dorman et al., 2003; 
 Kanatt et al., 2007; 
 Hui et al., 2010). Recently, the chemical diversity of this genus has been made accessible by genomics defining a repertory of metabolic genes that have contributed to the different chemotypes (
 Mint Evolutionary Genomics Consortium, 2018).
